 runs slow Cause: Section 2 has expensive operations Fix: # Before: Load full dataset (1M rows) df = pd.read_csv(&#39;data.csv&#39;) # After: Sample for development df = pd.read_csv(&#39;data.csv&#39;, nrows=10000) # Change back to full data when finalizing 12.4.3 Issue: Results don’t match when rerun Cause: Missing random seed setting Fix: # In Section 1 Setup import random np.random.seed(CONFIG[&#39;random_state&#39;]) random.seed(CONFIG[&#39;random_state&#39;]) # In model training model = RandomForestClassifier( random_state=CONFIG[&#39;random_state&#39;] ) 12.5 Asking Claude About Notebooks I&#39;m building a data science notebook for [task]. Current structure: SECTION 1: [what&#39;s in setup] SECTION 2: [what&#39;s in analysis] SECTION 3: [what&#39;s in outputs] Requirements: - [feature 1] - [feature 2] - [must be reproducible] Can you: 1. Review the structure 2. Suggest improvements 3. Show example cells Keep it professional and well-commented. 12.6 Exercise: Restructure an Existing Notebook Take one of your notebooks: Identify the sections (setup, analysis, outputs) Reorganize by section (even if messy) Add CONFIG dict with all paths and parameters Add section headers (markdown cells) Test: Restart kernel, run all, verify it works Compare before/after. Notice how much more organized it is! 12.7 Performance Tips 12.7.1 Tip 1: Use Sampling for Development # Quick iteration df_work = df.sample(n=10000, random_state=42) # Final run df_work = df.copy() 12.7.2 Tip 2: Cache Expensive Operations # First time: compute if not os.path.exists(&#39;processed_data.csv&#39;): df_processed = expensive_operation(df) df_processed.to_csv(&#39;processed_data.csv&#39;) else: # Subsequent times: load cached version df_processed = pd.read_csv(&#39;processed_data.csv&#39;) 12.7.3 Tip 3: Profile Slow Code import time start = time.time() # your code end = time.time() print(f&quot;Took {end - start:.2f} seconds&quot;) 12.8 Key Takeaways ✅ Use 3-section structure (Setup, Analysis, Output) ✅ Make Section 1 complete and standalone ✅ Run all from top every time ✅ Set random seeds and record environment versions for reproducibility ✅ Prevent leakage by splitting before learned preprocessing ✅ Compare held-out performance with a baseline ✅ Add progress messages and headers ✅ Save and document outputs ✅ Test with “Restart &amp; Run All”
